      "writtenOn": "2020-12-03T23:27:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We want to drop the task on fatal errors from the registered task handler. If the handler wants to retry a task on error, it can tag the error with either transient.Tag or tq.Retry tags. See https://godoc.org/go.chromium.org/luci/server/tq#Handler\n\nHow else do we communicate \"task failed to be processed and should be dropped\"? Returning an error is a natural way to signal errors. Such errors are logged and recorded in monitoring metrics etc. Asking handlers to return nil on fatal errors would mean we\u0027ll lose this information.",
      "parentUuid": "e140a929_4d1a2cd9",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 722,
        "startChar": 13,
        "endLine": 722,
        "endChar": 16
      },
      "revId": "851f0ef6d2fbe84ba8a0f42df506dd4966582230",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "1e2abfdd_c3912e0f",
        "filename": "server/tq/dispatcher.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 722,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-03T23:53:11Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "dropping a task unintentionally is expensive, because it is permanent.\nit is very easy to unintentionally not mark an error is transient (because this is now what people normally do). I think the default should be we retry, so that the developer has time to fix the situation, redeploy their code.\n\ni propose read transient.Tag and drop the task if only if the tag is there AND its value is false. This is in contrast to treating absence of tag as not-permanent.",
      "parentUuid": "3b4eefa1_d6d3e088",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 722,
        "startChar": 13,
        "endLine": 722,
        "endChar": 16
